      "routed_to": "Bird",
      "options": [
        "Option A: Cache keys locally with short TTL (e.g., 5 min). Enables offline for brief outages. Breaks instant revocation guarantee. May fail PCI-DSS audit.",
        "Option B: Queue-and-retry for KMS outages. No offline decryption. Payments degrade to 'pending' state. Preserves CMK security model fully.",
        "Option C: Redefine 'customer-managed' to mean policy control, not key custody. Simplest architecturally but changes the security promise."
      ],
      "recommendation": "Option B preserves the strongest security posture and is most likely to pass compliance review. Offline 'processing' can mean accepting and queuing payments (no encryption needed for the queue entry itself if using transport-level encryption), with decryption/settlement deferred until KMS is available."
    },
    {
      "type": "contradictory_requirements",
      "description": "Requirement 2 (50ms P99 including encryption/decryption) is in significant tension with Requirement 3 (every field access must be logged). A typical payment record has 8-15 sensitive fields. If audit logging is synchronous (which 'fully auditable' and 'every field access' implies), each log write adds 1-5ms depending on durability guarantees. With 10 fields, that's 10-50ms for audit alone — consuming the entire latency budget before any encryption or business logic. Options: (A) Async audit logging with guaranteed delivery — accept small window of unaudited access on crash, (B) Batched synchronous audit — log all field accesses in a single write per request rather than per field, (C) Relax P99 target to 100-200ms if synchronous per-field audit is truly required.",
      "routed_to": "Bird",
      "options": [
        "Option A: Async audit with append-only log and guaranteed delivery (e.g., Kafka). Sub-millisecond on hot path. Tiny crash-loss window.",
        "Option B: Batch audit — one log entry per request listing all fields accessed. Synchronous but O(1) writes instead of O(fields). Changes audit granularity.",
        "Option C: Relax P99 to 150ms to accommodate synchronous per-field logging. Requires product sign-off on latency."
      ],
      "recommendation": "Option B (batched audit) is the pragmatic middle ground — one synchronous write per payment operation that records all fields accessed in that operation. This preserves full auditability, keeps latency under control, and avoids the crash-loss window of async logging."
    }
  ],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 40,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "Envelope encryption is the correct pattern for the key hierarchy regardless of how contradictions are resolved",
      "Zero-downtime key rotation is achievable via envelope encryption with DEK re-wrapping",
      "The CMK vs offline contradiction is real and cannot be resolved architecturally alone"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Whether local key caching is acceptable from a compliance perspective",
      "Whether audit logging must be synchronous or eventual consistency is acceptable",
      "Whether 50ms P99 is achievable with the required audit granularity",
      "The actual latency characteristics of the customer's KMS (critical for sizing the cache TTL and fallback strategy)"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "CMK refers to a model similar to AWS KMS CMK / Azure Key Vault / GCP Cloud KMS where key material lives in the customer's account",
      "Payment records contain multiple sensitive fields (PAN, CVV, cardholder name, etc.) each requiring individual encryption and audit",
      "The 50ms P99 target is measured at the service boundary, not end-to-end including network",
      "PCI-DSS compliance is a hard requirement given this is payment processing"
    ]
  }
}

